   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="transcription">
            <p>
<lb corresp="#a1"/><gap reason="lost"/><w>-ne</w><pc>॥</pc><w>tane</w><w>rṣakāñcca</w>
<lb corresp="#a2"/><gap reason="lost"/><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><pc>॥</pc><w>tane</w><w>rṣakāñcca</w>
<w>śa<lb corresp="#b1"/><supplied>ci</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/><w>-śk<gap reason="plain" unit="part"/></w><w>aimar</w><pc>॥</pc><w>tumeṃ</w>
<w>rṣa<lb corresp="#b2"/><supplied>kāñcca</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/><w>ky<supplied>ā</supplied>na</w><gap reason="plain" quantity="1"/><w>ñī</w><w>tañ</w><w>lo<milestone unit="w" type="break"/></w></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Then the [female] sage (Śacī)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... Then the [female] sage Śa(cī)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">"... I will bring the dear ..." . Thereupon the [female] sa(ge Śacī)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (s)he (?) fulfilled my ... your ...</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">Note the double consonant <hi>rṣakāñcca</hi> for <hi>rṣakāñca</hi> 'female sage'.</note><note type="remarks">Small fragment from the right part of a five-line leaf with the right margin preserved. Partly edited in <bibl><title corresp="ref:siegandsiegling1953"/><citedRange>323</citedRange></bibl> sub no. 354.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">-<hi>śk(·)</hi> is the end of a diminutive form.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment"><hi>ky(ā)na</hi> is the causative preterite of <hi>kän</hi>- ‘fulfill'; since the following sign is unreadable (certainly not <hi>ṣṣäṃ</hi> as read by Tamai), it may also be another person of that stem.</note></p>
         </div>
